{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8925e5d1-be23-4670-a1c1-12b1e864be42","content":"I see your code uses `IFileSystem` from `System.IO.Abstractions`. Could you clarify what kind of wrapper you need? A few possibilities:\n\n1. **A simplified service interface** — a custom `IFileSystemWrapper` with common operations (read, write, exists, delete) that delegates to `IFileSystem`, making it easier to mock in tests.\n2. **A DI registration helper** — wiring up the real `FileSystem` implementation in your service container.\n3. **A decorator/logging wrapper** — an `IFileSystem` implementation that adds logging/metrics around file operations.\n\nWhich of these (or something else) are you looking for?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c9353725-325d-4503-8fc5-935e8d7cf075","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user already uses `IFileSystem` from `System.IO.Abstractions` and wants a file system wrapper. They likely want a wrapper class that wraps around the real `System.IO.Abstractions.FileSystem` implementation — something they can register in DI as a concrete implementation of `IFileSystem`, or perhaps a custom wrapper/abstraction layer.\n\nActually, looking at this more carefully, `System.IO.Abstractions` already provides `FileSystem` as the real implementation of `IFileSystem`. So what kind of \"wrapper\" do they want?\n\nPossibilities:\n1. A wrapper around the real file system that implements `IFileSystem` - but that already exists as `FileSystem` in the package.\n\n\n2. A custom wrapper interface that's simpler than `IFileSystem` but delegates to it.\n3. A mock/test wrapper.\n\nMost likely they're looking for a simplified abstraction layer that bundles common file operations into a single, easier-to-mock service interface rather than exposing the full complexity of `IFileSystem`.\n\nSince `System.IO.Abstractions` already provides a concrete `FileSystem` implementation, I should clarify with the user what specific wrapper pattern they need.","outputTo